 (3-1) had another strong start and a second straight win in which he allowed a leadoff homer after doing the same in Baltimore on Monday. In five innings he allowed three runs and four hits while striking out seven. Riley Greene hit the third pitch of the game for a 360-foot homer to right. The Tigers also scored two runs in the fourth when Juan Soto misplayed a hit into the rightfield corner that became an RBI triple for Matt Vierling. He would score on a sac fly from Colt Keith.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eCaleb Ferguson relieved Schmidt to start the sixth and lasted just a third of an inning leaving the two potential tying runs on base. Of course it was a pitcher named Luke (Weaver) who was able to restore order to the Yankees universe in this Star Wars-themed game. Weaver wrapped up the sixth on four pitches —\u0026nbsp;a strikeout and a fly out —\u0026nbsp;then provided a 1-2-3 seventh and gave the Yankees two outs in the eighth.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eClay Holmes delivered a four-out save.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eThe Yankees bullpen has not allowed an earned run in 21 2/3 innings.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eWhile the process was generally routine, the oddity of the day came in the seventh when Aaron Judge was ejected for the first time in his career after grousing over a called third strike. Judge took the pitch, which appeared to catch the outside edge of the strike zone, and walked away complaining. He made it about three long strides toward the dugout before home plate umpire Ryan Blakney tossed him.\u003c/p\u003e \n\u003cp\u003eIt wasn’t as if Judge had frustration bubbling; his hit in the ninth on Friday night ignited a Yankees comeback win and he had two hits, scored twice, and drove in a run earlier in this game. He tied the score at 1 in the first on Giancarlo Stanton’s RBI single.\u003c/p\u003e","publishedDate":"2024-05-04T19:59:42.073Z","updatedDate":"2024-05-04T20:21:46.390Z","url":"https://www.newsday.com/sports/baseball/yankees/yank